The recursive helper can be replaced entirely with `list.find`:

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/transaction.{Input, OutputReference}

fn locate_input(inputs: List<Input>, target: OutputReference) -> Option<Input> {
  list.find(inputs, fn(input) { input.output_reference == target })
}
```

`list.find` already performs the same left-to-right scan and short-circuits on the first match, so no manual recursion is needed.

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/assets
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, Input}

validator guarded_mint {
  mint(
    _redeemer: Void,
    policy_id: assets.PolicyId,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    let has_policy_input =
      list.find(
        self.inputs,
        fn(input: Input) {
          assets.quantity_of(input.output.value, policy_id, assets.ada_asset_name) > 0
            || list.length(assets.policies(input.output.value)) > 0
            && list.find(
                assets.policies(input.output.value),
                fn(p) { p == policy_id },
              )
              != None
        },
      )
    has_policy_input != None
  }
}
```

`list.find` searches a list and returns the first element satisfying a predicate as `Option<a>` — you get the original element back unchanged.

`list.find_map` also searches, but simultaneously transforms the found element. Its predicate returns `Option<result>` — returning `Some(value)` means "found it AND here is the transformed value", while `None` means "keep searching".

Signatures:
```aiken
// find: returns the element itself
pub fn find(self: List<a>, predicate: fn(a) -> Bool) -> Option<a>

// find_map: returns a transformed result
pub fn find_map(self: List<a>, predicate: fn(a) -> Option<result>) -> Option<result>
```

Prefer `find` when you need the raw element. Prefer `find_map` when you need to locate an element AND derive a value from it in one pass — avoiding a second `map` call over the `Option` result and iterating the list only once.

Example:
```aiken
use aiken/collection/list

// Instead of:
let maybe_elem = list.find(inputs, fn(i) { i.output_reference == target })
let maybe_value = option.map(maybe_elem, fn(i) { i.output.value })

// Use find_map for a single traversal:
let maybe_value =
  list.find_map(
    inputs,
    fn(i) {
      if i.output_reference == target {
        Some(i.output.value)
      } else {
        None
      }
    },
  )
```

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use cardano/assets
use cardano/transaction.{OutputReference, Transaction, Input}

validator check_input_lovelace {
  spend(
    _datum: Option<Void>,
    redeemer: OutputReference,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    let target = redeemer
    let maybe_lovelace =
      list.find_map(
        self.inputs,
        fn(input: Input) -> Option<Int> {
          if input.output_reference == target {
            Some(assets.lovelace_of(input.output.value))
          } else {
            None
          }
        },
      )
    when maybe_lovelace is {
      Some(lovelace) -> lovelace >= 2_000_000
      None -> False
    }
  }
}
```

`list.find_map` retorna `None` cuando ningún elemento produce `Some(...)` al aplicarle el predicado.

Firma de la función:
```aiken
pub fn find_map(
  self: List<a>,
  predicate: fn(a) -> Option<result>,
) -> Option<result>
```

La función recorre la lista de izquierda a derecha. Para cada elemento:
- Si el predicado devuelve `Some(value)`, la búsqueda se detiene y retorna `Some(value)`.
- Si el predicado devuelve `None`, continúa con el siguiente elemento.

Si la lista se agota sin encontrar ningún `Some(...)`, el resultado final es `None`.

Ejemplo:
```aiken
use aiken/collection/list

let result =
  list.find_map(
    [1, 2, 3],
    fn(x) {
      if x > 10 {
        Some(x * 2)
      } else {
        None
      }
    },
  )
// result == None
```

