Para representar el intervalo abierto (20, +∞) — es decir, todos los valores estrictamente mayores que 20 — puedes usar la función `entirely_after` de `aiken/interval`:

```aiken
use aiken/interval

let i: Interval = interval.entirely_after(20)
```

O construirlo manualmente con el struct `Interval`:

```aiken
use aiken/interval.{Interval, IntervalBound}

let i: Interval =
  Interval {
    lower_bound: IntervalBound { bound_type: Finite(20), is_inclusive: False },
    upper_bound: IntervalBound { bound_type: PositiveInfinity, is_inclusive: False },
  }
```

El campo `is_inclusive: False` en el límite inferior indica que el punto 20 **no** está incluido en el intervalo.

`interval.between(lower, upper)` creates a **closed** interval [lower, upper] where both endpoints are **inclusive** — the interval contains both `lower` and `upper`.

`interval.entirely_between(lower, upper)` creates an **open** interval (lower, upper) where both endpoints are **exclusive** — the interval contains only values strictly between `lower` and `upper`, not the endpoints themselves.

Example:
```aiken
use aiken/interval

// [5, 15] — includes 5 and 15
let closed = interval.between(5, 15)

// (5, 15) — excludes 5 and 15
let open = interval.entirely_between(5, 15)

// contains checks:
interval.contains(closed, 5)  // True
interval.contains(open, 5)    // False
interval.contains(closed, 10) // True
interval.contains(open, 10)   // True
```

Choose `between` when your bounds are inclusive (e.g., a deadline slot that itself is valid), and `entirely_between` when the bounds are exclusive.

