El validador extrae `start_time` y `end_time` del datum, construye el intervalo cerrado `[start_time, end_time]` con `interval.between`, y luego comprueba que el `validity_range` de la transacción quede completamente contenido en dicha ventana usando `interval.includes`.

`interval.entirely_between(lower_bound, upper_bound)` creates an open interval that **excludes both bounds**, i.e. the mathematical notation $(lower\_bound, upper\_bound)$. Both `is_inclusive` fields are set to `False`.

In contrast, `interval.between(lower_bound, upper_bound)` creates a **closed** interval $[lower\_bound, upper\_bound]$ where both bounds are **inclusive**.

Example:
```aiken
use aiken/interval

// Open interval: 10 and 100 are NOT included
let open = interval.entirely_between(10, 100)
// interval.contains(open, 10) == False
// interval.contains(open, 50) == True
// interval.contains(open, 100) == False

// Closed interval: 10 and 100 ARE included
let closed = interval.between(10, 100)
// interval.contains(closed, 10) == True
// interval.contains(closed, 100) == True
```

```aiken
use aiken/interval
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}

validator auction_window {
  spend(
    _datum: Option<Void>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    let auction_range = interval.entirely_between(1000, 5000)
    interval.includes(auction_range, self.validity_range)
  }
}
```
This uses `interval.entirely_between(1000, 5000)` to build the open interval $(1000, 5000)$ and then checks that the transaction's validity range is fully contained within it using `interval.includes`.

Puedes usar `interval.entirely_between` junto con `interval.includes` de la siguiente manera:

```aiken
use aiken/interval
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction, OutputReference}

validator time_locked {
  spend(
    _datum: Option<Void>,
    _redeemer: Void,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    self: Transaction,
