## Behavior of `bytearray.at` on Out-of-Bounds Index

`bytearray.at(self: ByteArray, index: Int) -> Byte` **crashes the program** (halts execution) if the index does not exist in the ByteArray. There is no `Option` wrapping — it either returns the byte or fails entirely.

## Safe Usage Pattern

To use it safely in a validator, guard the call by first checking the length of the ByteArray using `bytearray.length` (if available) or by structuring your logic so the byte array is guaranteed to have sufficient length.

A common defensive pattern is to ensure the datum or input has a known fixed structure:

```aiken
use aiken/primitive/bytearray
use cardano/transaction.{OutputReference, Transaction}

validator safe_byte_check {
  spend(
    datum: Option<ByteArray>,
    _redeemer: Data,
    _own_ref: OutputReference,
    _self: Transaction,
  ) -> Bool {
    when datum is {
      None -> False
      Some(data) ->
        // Only access index 0 if we know data is exactly 4 bytes
        // (enforced by minting policy or construction)
        bytearray.at(data, 0) == 0xDE &&
        bytearray.at(data, 1) == 0xAD
    }
  }
}
```

> **Key takeaway:** Unlike `list.at` which returns `Option<a>`, `bytearray.at` is unsafe by design. Validate the structure of your ByteArray before indexing into it.

```aiken
use aiken/primitive/bytearray
use cardano/assets.{PolicyId}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}

validator nft_prefix_check {
