`assets.has_any_nft_strict(value, policy)` checks whether a `Value` carries **exactly one NFT** from the given policy **and nothing else besides Ada**. It returns `False` if the value contains any other non-Ada assets (even from the same policy). In contrast, `assets.has_any_nft` only checks that at least one NFT from the policy is present, without caring about other assets.

Examples from the docs:

```aiken
// Value with one NFT from "foo" plus another asset from "bar" → strict fails
let value = assets.from_lovelace(42)
  |> assets.add("foo", "asset#1", 1)
  |> assets.add("bar", "asset#2", 14)
assets.has_any_nft_strict(value, "foo") == False

// Value with exactly one NFT from "foo" → strict passes
let value2 = assets.from_lovelace(42)
  |> assets.add("foo", "asset#1", 1)
assets.has_any_nft_strict(value2, "foo") == True

// Value with two NFTs from "foo" → strict fails (quantity > 1 per token or multiple tokens)
let value3 = assets.from_lovelace(42)
  |> assets.add("foo", "asset#1", 1)
  |> assets.add("foo", "asset#2", 1)
assets.has_any_nft_strict(value3, "foo") == False
```

